            <div class="prose max-w-none" x-show="lang === 'en'" x-cloak>
                <h2>Step 1: Identify the Suspension Reason Before Taking Action</h2>
<p>Submitting an appeal without understanding why your account was suspended wastes everyone's time. Log into your Google Ads backend and check the "Account Status" page for specific suspension details. Common reasons include suspicious payment activity, policy violations, unusual traffic patterns, or invalid activity.</p>
<h3>Checklist</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Screenshot and save the Account Status page</li>
<li>[ ] Record the error code (e.g., CPA-xxx series)</li>
<li>[ ] Confirm whether it's account-level suspension or campaign-level pause</li>
</ul>
<h2>Step 2: Gather Essential Documentation</h2>
<p>Appeal materials must prove you're a legitimate business operating within Google Ads policies. Here's your baseline documentation checklist:</p>
<h3>Checklist</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Business license or company registration documents (must match account holder)</li>
<li>[ ] Legal representative's ID (front and back)</li>
<li>[ ] Domain ownership proof (WHOIS info or hosting dashboard screenshot)</li>
<li>[ ] Recent advertising spend bills or payment records</li>
</ul>
<h2>Step 3: Prepare Case-Specific Supporting Materials</h2>
<p>Different violation types require different evidence. This is where most advertisers make mistakes.</p>
<h3>For Product/Service Quality Complaints</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Third-party testing reports or certifications (FDA, CE, etc.)</li>
<li>[ ] Screenshots of refund policies and after-sales service pages</li>
<li>[ ] Records of resolved customer complaints</li>
</ul>
<h3>For Ad Creative Policy Violations</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Revised ad copy and final image designs</li>
<li>[ ] Screenshots of ad landing pages and their content</li>
<li>[ ] Documentation of specific creative changes made</li>
</ul>
<h3>For Traffic Quality or Invalid Activity Issues</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Google Analytics data showing normal traffic sources</li>
<li>[ ] Third-party ad attribution reports (Adjust, AppsFlyer, etc.)</li>
<li>[ ] Description of anti-fraud measures already implemented</li>
</ul>
<h2>Step 4: Draft a Professional Appeal Message</h2>
<p>Your email is the reviewer's first impression—structure it clearly and keep the tone professional.</p>
<h3>Email Structure Template</h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>Opening</strong>: Account ID + brief description of the violation</li>
<li><strong>Self-analysis</strong>: Your understanding of the likely cause</li>
<li><strong>Remediation</strong>: Specific corrective actions already taken</li>
<li><strong>Commitment</strong>: Assurance of future policy compliance</li>
<li><strong>Attachment list</strong>: Enumerating all submitted evidence</li>
</ol>
<h3>Checklist</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Write in the official language of your account's registered region</li>
<li>[ ] Avoid emotional language or blaming the reviewer</li>
<li>[ ] Keep the email under 300-500 words</li>
<li>[ ] Use consistent file naming (e.g., <code>BusinessLicense_2024.pdf</code>)</li>
</ul>
<h2>Step 5: Submit and Follow Up</h2>
<p>After preparing your materials, submit through official channels and track progress diligently.</p>
<h3>Checklist</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Submit through the official Google Ads help page, not via reply emails</li>
<li>[ ] Record submission date and set a 5-7 business day follow-up reminder</li>
<li>[ ] Send a follow-up if no response after 10 business days</li>
<li>[ ] Do not appeal the same account more than twice within 30 days</li>
</ul>
<h2>Additional Reminders</h2>
<ul>
<li>If you manage multiple accounts under one advertiser, avoid appealing suspended and active accounts simultaneously—this can trigger related account reviews</li>
<li>Prepaid balances typically <strong>cannot be transferred</strong> until the appeal is resolved—plan your budget accordingly</li>
<li>If your first appeal is rejected, carefully read the specific policy clauses cited—<strong>don't resubmit identical materials</strong></li>
</ul>
<p>With this checklist ready, you'll find that preparing appeal materials isn't as daunting as it seems. The key is pinpointing the cause, gathering solid evidence, and clearly demonstrating your corrective actions. Show the reviewer you're committed to compliance, and they'll likely give your account another chance.</p>
